  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered a violation of the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unequivocally a violation of the law in virtually every country. Here's a structured overview:\n\n1. **Definition**: Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained funds (e.g., from drug trafficking, corruption, or fraud) to make them appear legitimate.\n\n2. **Legality**:\n   - **Global Recognition**: It is criminalized internationally through frameworks like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** and the **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime**.\n   - **National Laws**: Countries enforce their own statutes, such as:\n     - **U.S.**: Money Laundering Control Act (1986), with penalties up to 20 years imprisonment.\n     - **U.K.**: Proceeds of Crime Act (2002).\n     - **EU**: Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD), including stringent reporting and transparency requirements.\n\n3. **Penalties**: Severe consequences include imprisonment, hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and reputational damage. Even aiding in laundering (e.g., through shell companies or smurfing) is illegal.\n\n4. **Institutional Compliance**: Financial institutions must implement **Anti-Money Laundering (AML)** measures, such as **Know Your Customer (KYC)** checks and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\n5. **Distinction from Related Crimes**: While tax evasion (hiding income) is separate, both it and money laundering are illegal. Laundering focuses on obscuring the **source** of funds.\n\n6. **No Legal Exceptions**: No jurisdiction permits money laundering. Even historically secretive banking systems (e.g., Switzerland) now comply with international AML standards.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious, universally condemned crime with robust legal frameworks aimed at detecting, preventing, and punishing offenders.",
